            {
              "id": "017867c7-46ca-3695-9489-5cc0c185ef43",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerabilities from User-Controlled Data in Methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn JavaScript, methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write` can introduce XSS vulnerabilities if they are used to insert user-controlled data into the DOM. These methods interpret the inserted data as HTML, which can include potentially harmful scripts.\n\nIn the provided code example, the `innerHTML` method is used to insert user-controlled data (`t.minutes`) into the DOM, which can lead to an XSS vulnerability if `t.minutes` contains a malicious script.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities from user-controlled data in methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write`, you should:\n\n- Use text content methods like `textContent` or `innerText` instead of `innerHTML` or `outerHTML` when inserting user-controlled data into the DOM. These methods do not interpret the inserted data as HTML, preventing potential scripts from being executed.\n- If you need to insert HTML into the DOM, use methods or libraries that automatically escape potentially harmful characters, such as the `innerText` property or jQuery's `text()` method.\n- Validate and sanitize user input to ensure it does not contain potentially harmful scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code example can be fixed by using the `textContent` method instead of `innerHTML`:\n\n```javascript\nminutesSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.minutes).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0186b93f-220b-35f8-a4e8-648bf8ad1339",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerabilities from User-Controlled Data in Methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn JavaScript, methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write` can introduce XSS vulnerabilities if they are used to insert user-controlled data into the DOM. The specific code example `hoursItem.innerHTML = ('0' + time.hours).slice(-2);` is vulnerable to XSS if `time.hours` is user-controlled and not properly sanitized.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use the principle of least privilege: Only allow necessary permissions for the code that handles user input.\n- Validate input: Ensure that user input matches expected patterns.\n- Escape untrusted HTTP request data: HTML, URL, JavaScript, CSS, and attribute escaping should be applied.\n- Use secure APIs: Avoid using APIs, like `innerHTML`, that can execute code. Instead, use text APIs, like `textContent` or `innerText`, which cannot execute code.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP): This can be used as a defense-in-depth measure to mitigate against the risks of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nA safer way to update the `hoursItem` element would be to use `textContent` instead of `innerHTML`:\n\n```javascript\nhoursItem.textContent = ('0' + time.hours).slice(-2);\n```\n\nThis code does not have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "032da9b8-46ec-313e-abfb-186035f5d883",
              "name": "\"addEventListener API Vulnerability to Cross Origin Attacks and XSS due to Lack of Origin Validation\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `addEventListener` API in JavaScript is used to register an event handler to a specific event such as 'click', 'load', 'resize', etc. on a specific element. However, if not properly validated, it can be exploited to perform Cross-Origin attacks and Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\nIn Cross-Origin attacks, an attacker can make a request to a different domain, subdomain, or protocol, which can lead to data theft or manipulation. In XSS attacks, an attacker can inject malicious scripts into webpages viewed by other users, which can lead to session hijacking, identity theft, defacement of websites, and other potential security risks.\n\nIn the given code snippet, an event listener is added to the window object for the 'resize' event. However, there is no validation of the origin of the event, which can lead to the aforementioned vulnerabilities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always validate the origin of the event. This can be done by checking the `origin` property of the event object, which contains the origin of the document that initiated the event.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the given code snippet:\n\n```javascript\nwindow.addEventListener('resize', function(event) {\n    if (event.origin !== 'http://trusted.origin.com') {\n        return;\n    }\n    resizer(event);\n}, false);\n```\n\nIn this code, the origin of the event is checked before the `resizer` function is called. If the origin is not the expected one, the function returns immediately, preventing any potential attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe given code snippet does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP: Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-346: Origin Validation Error](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-345",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-345"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0483fa46-049f-3a76-aa51-ff7fc74d42af",
              "name": "Detected Insecure Deserialization Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure deserialization is a vulnerability that occurs when untrusted data is deserialized by a program. This can lead to harmful consequences such as remote code execution, where an attacker can run arbitrary code on the victim's machine. In JavaScript, this vulnerability can occur when using functions like `eval()` or `Function()` to deserialize data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid deserializing data from untrusted sources. If deserialization is necessary, use safe alternatives like `JSON.parse()`. This function only parses JSON-formatted data, and does not evaluate the data as code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of a vulnerable code snippet and how to fix it:\n\n**Vulnerable Code:**\n\n```javascript\nvar user = eval('(' + req.body.user + ')');\n```\n\n**Fixed Code:**\n\n```javascript\nvar user = JSON.parse(req.body.user);\n```\n\nIn the fixed code, `JSON.parse()` is used instead of `eval()`. This prevents the server from evaluating potentially harmful code contained in `req.body.user`.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A8-Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [OWASP Cheat Sheet: Deserialization Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Deserialization_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html)\n\nPlease note that all the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-502",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-502"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "083d75cb-7408-3c71-a56c-5cfab9eb3d62",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A type of XSS vulnerability is when user-controlled data in a HTML string may result in XSS. This happens when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing HTML page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, it is important to:\n\n1. **Escape user input**: This means that you should make sure that any user input is properly escaped, so that it is treated as data rather than code.\n\n2. **Validate user input**: You should not trust user input and should validate it on the server side as well as on the client side.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly cookies**: This attribute can help to mitigate the impact of a potential XSS attack by preventing an attacker from accessing the session cookie via JavaScript.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to escape user input in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\nvar userInput = \"<script>malicious code here</script>\";\nvar safeInput = escape(userInput);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `escape` function is used to make sure that the user input is treated as data rather than code.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0898d979-f478-333e-b280-2a37e9d0431b",
              "name": "Potential ReDoS Vulnerability Due to RegExp() Function Argument 'c' in Application: Consider Using Hardcoded Regexes, Input Validation, or Regex Checking/Sanitization Libraries for Security.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code has a potential Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) vulnerability due to the use of the `RegExp()` function. ReDoS is a type of Denial of Service attack where a regular expression (or RegExp) can cause the program to enter an extreme situation, causing it to work very slowly. This can happen when the RegExp used is vulnerable to catastrophic backtracking.\n\nIn this case, the `RegExp()` function is used with a variable argument 'c', which can be manipulated to cause the application to slow down or even freeze, leading to a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, consider the following:\n\n1. Avoid using the `RegExp()` function with user-supplied input. Instead, use hardcoded regular expressions whenever possible.\n2. Validate and sanitize input before using it in a regular expression. This can prevent malicious input from causing a ReDoS attack.\n3. Use libraries that can check or sanitize regular expressions to prevent ReDoS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is the use of `RegExp()` function with the argument 'c'. A potential fix could be to validate and sanitize 'c' before using it in the `RegExp()` function. However, without the full context of the code, it's hard to provide a specific fix.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to be obfuscated and it's hard to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to reference `SyntaxHighlighter` and `XRegExp`, so these might be required for the code to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1333",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1333.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1333"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "08e4be51-f0e2-3830-8e61-c4652b3373ce",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A type of XSS vulnerability is when user-controlled data in a HTML string may result in XSS. This happens when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing HTML page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, it is important to:\n\n1. **Escape user input**: This means that you should make sure that any user input is properly escaped, so that it is treated as data rather than code.\n\n2. **Validate user input**: You should not trust user input and should validate it on the server side as well as on the client side.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly cookies**: This attribute can help to mitigate the impact of a potential XSS attack by preventing an attacker from accessing the session cookie via JavaScript.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to escape user input in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\nvar userInput = \"<script>malicious code here</script>\";\nvar safeInput = escape(userInput);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `escape` function is used to make sure that the user input is treated as data rather than code.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
