            {
              "id": "0a3a113d-9558-32cd-b1c0-ccab96d51e78",
              "name": "\"Replace `math/rand` with `crypto/rand` due to Security Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `math/rand` package is used for generating pseudo-random numbers. However, it is not suitable for generating random numbers in a security-sensitive context, as it uses a deterministic source to generate random numbers. This means that if an attacker can predict the seed value, they can predict the sequence of random numbers generated by `math/rand`.\n\nOn the other hand, `crypto/rand` package generates random numbers from sources that a cryptographic algorithm deems as unpredictable, making it suitable for generating random numbers in a security-sensitive context.\n\nUsing `math/rand` instead of `crypto/rand` in a security-sensitive context is a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, replace `math/rand` with `crypto/rand` in your Go code whenever you need to generate random numbers in a security-sensitive context.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace:\n\n```go\nimport \"math/rand\"\n\nfunc generateToken() string {\n    b := make([]byte, 16)\n    rand.Read(b)\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%x\", b)\n}\n```\n\nWith:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/rand\"\n\nfunc generateToken() string {\n    b := make([]byte, 16)\n    _, err := rand.Read(b)\n    if err != nil {\n        log.Fatal(err)\n    }\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%x\", b)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/rand`\n- `fmt`\n- `log`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Randomness](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Randomness)\n- [CWE-338: Use of Cryptographically Weak PRNG](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-338",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-338"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0ac44fe2-07bb-3c2a-b684-39474350360f",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of injection security vulnerability where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. In JavaScript, particularly when using jQuery's `html()` function, this vulnerability can be exploited if user input is not properly sanitized before being rendered on the webpage.\n\nThe `html()` function in jQuery sets or returns the content (innerHTML) of selected elements. However, if this function is used to include user input without proper sanitization, it can lead to XSS attacks. This is because the `html()` function does not escape any HTML and JavaScript content, which means that any script included in the input will be executed when the content is rendered.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `text()` function instead of `html()` when the string is plain text. The `text()` function escapes the HTML and ensures that any included script is not executed.\n\nIf the string contains HTML that needs to be rendered, use a function that escapes HTML such as edx's `HtmlUtils.setHtml()`. This function ensures that any script included in the input is not executed when the content is rendered.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```javascript\n$(\"#element\").html(userInput);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```javascript\n$(\"#element\").text(userInput);\n```\n\nOr, if HTML needs to be rendered:\n\n```javascript\nHtmlUtils.setHtml($(\"#element\"), userInput);\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0acdf740-4b5c-3bd1-8787-b5249b7769f6",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn this case, the potential XSS vulnerability arises from the use of jQuery's `html()` function. This function gets the HTML contents of the first element in the set of matched elements or set the HTML contents of every matched element. However, if you use the `html()` method to manipulate the HTML content of an element, you are exposed to this vulnerability because the method does not escape the string to be used as HTML.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function with user-supplied input. Instead, use the `text()` function for plain strings, which automatically escapes HTML tags, or use `HtmlUtils.setHtml()` for HTML escaping.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```javascript\nlabel.html(msg);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```javascript\nlabel.text(msg);\n```\n\nOr, if you need to include HTML tags in the message:\n\n```javascript\nlabel.html(HtmlUtils.setHtml(msg));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- jQuery\n- HtmlUtils (if you choose to use `HtmlUtils.setHtml()`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0c8e9010-5950-30a4-99a7-2ef4ff061d88",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, it's important to:\n\n1. **Validate Input:** Validate user input to ensure it conforms to the expected format, using a whitelist of acceptable inputs.\n\n2. **Encode Output:** Encode user-supplied data when it is output in HTML, JavaScript, or other contexts.\n\n3. **Use Appropriate Response Headers:** To prevent XSS in HTTP responses that aren't intended to contain any HTML or JavaScript, you can use the Content-Type and X-Content-Type-Options headers to ensure that browsers interpret the responses the way you intend.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy:** Use Content Security Policy (CSP) as a safety net to mitigate the impact of any XSS which does occur.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is the use of user-controlled data in jQuery's `$()` function, which can lead to DOM-based XSS. \n\n```javascript\n$(input)\n```\n\nTo fix this, you should avoid using user-controlled data in this context. If you need to use user-controlled data to select an element, you should use a safer method like `getElementById`:\n\n```javascript\ndocument.getElementById(input)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
