            {
              "id": "124790d2-7a1c-3abf-9f02-909c6357d9e3",
              "name": "Unhashed Password Storage Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnhashed Password Storage Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of storing passwords in plaintext format in a database. This is a serious security vulnerability because if an attacker gains access to the database, they can easily read and misuse the passwords. In the provided Go code, the password is being stored as a plaintext string in the database, which is a clear instance of this vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best practice to mitigate this vulnerability is to never store passwords in plaintext. Instead, passwords should be hashed using a strong cryptographic hash function before they are stored. When a user logs in, the entered password is hashed again and the hash is compared with the stored hash. This way, even if an attacker gains access to the database, they cannot reverse-engineer the original password from the hash.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code using the bcrypt library to hash the passwords:\n\n```go\nimport \"golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt\"\n\nhashedPassword, err := bcrypt.GenerateFromPassword([]byte(fmt.Sprintf(\"secret password %d\", i)), bcrypt.DefaultCost)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\n_, err = db.Exec(\n    \"INSERT INTO user (name, email, password) VALUES (?, ?, ?)\",\n    fmt.Sprintf(\"User %d\", i),\n    fmt.Sprintf(\"user%d@mail.com\", i),\n    hashedPassword)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `database/sql`: Standard Go library for SQL interaction.\n- `fmt`: Standard Go library for formatted I/O operations.\n- `golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt`: Go supplementary cryptography libraries for password hashing.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-256",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/256.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-256"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "135b1ed4-3832-3625-9aa9-e2c969dff8fc",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn this case, the vulnerability is related to the use of jQuery's `html()` function. This function can potentially introduce XSS vulnerabilities because it interprets the argument as HTML. If this argument is in any way derived from user input, it can lead to a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function with user-supplied input. Instead, use the `text()` function, which treats the input as plain text, not as HTML code. If you need to include HTML tags in the output, make sure to properly escape them to prevent any code execution.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.html(text_single);\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.text(text_single);\n```\n\nIf you need to include HTML tags in the output, use a function that properly escapes them. For example, if you are using the Underscore.js library, you can use the `_.escape()` function:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.html(_.escape(text_single));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "15d4fabe-37d8-3ed9-aff7-edc7447997ff",
              "name": "\"`secondsItem` User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern Leading to XSS Vulnerabilities\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `secondsItem` User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern Leading to XSS Vulnerabilities is a type of Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability that occurs when user-controlled data is directly included in a web page without properly sanitizing the input. In this case, the `secondsItem.innerHTML` is being set to a value that is derived from user-controlled data (`time.seconds`). If an attacker can control the value of `time.seconds`, they can inject malicious scripts into the web page, which will be executed when the page is loaded.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user-controlled data before including it in a web page. This can be done by using a safe method to set the content of an element, such as `textContent`, or by using a library or function that automatically sanitizes the input.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```javascript\nsecondsItem.textContent = ('0' + time.seconds).slice(-2);\n```\n\nIn this fix, `textContent` is used instead of `innerHTML`. The `textContent` property sets or returns the text content of the specified node, and all its descendants. If you set the textContent property, any child nodes are removed and replaced by a single Text node containing the specified string.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not appear to have any specific library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
