            {
              "id": "4088c7e4-e50d-340e-8631-a604cc1ee8ec",
              "name": "Potential ReDoS vulnerability due to RegExp() being called with a `c` function argument in your application. Consider using hardcoded regexes, input validation, or a regex checking/sanitization library like 'recheck'.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `RegExp()` function in JavaScript is used to create a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern. When this function is called with a `c` function argument, it can potentially allow an attacker to cause a Regular Expression Denial-of-Service (ReDoS) within your application. This is because the `RegExp()` function blocks the main thread, causing the application to hang or become unresponsive.\n\nReDoS is a form of Denial of Service (DoS) attack that exploits the fact that most Regular Expression implementations may reach extreme situations that cause them to work very slowly (exponentially related to input size). An attacker can then cause a program using a Regular Expression to enter these extreme situations and then hang for a very long time.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use hardcoded regular expressions instead of dynamically creating them with the `RegExp()` function. If your regular expression is run on user-controlled input, consider performing input validation to ensure that the input is safe before running the regular expression on it.\n\nYou can also use a regular expression checking/sanitization library such as [recheck](https://www.npmjs.com/package/recheck) to verify that the regular expression does not appear vulnerable to ReDoS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `RegExp()` with a `c` function argument, use a hardcoded regular expression. For example, instead of:\n\n```javascript\nvar re = new RegExp(userInput);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```javascript\nvar re = /hardcoded_regex/;\n```\n\nAnd if you need to use user input in your regular expression, validate the input first:\n\n```javascript\nif (isValid(userInput)) {\n    var re = new RegExp(userInput);\n}\n```\n\n## Resources\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1333",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1333.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
