            {
              "id": "42dbe0af-d9ac-3e40-b94f-0093ca71cb30",
              "name": "Redundant Variable Assignment",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, the vulnerability \"`c` is assigned twice; the first assignment is useless\" refers to a situation where a variable `c` is assigned a value twice in a row, without the first value being used. This is a code quality issue that can lead to confusion and potential bugs. It's not a security vulnerability per se, but it can contribute to them by making the code harder to understand and maintain.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, developers should ensure that they only assign values to variables when necessary. If a variable is assigned a value that is never used, this is a sign that the code is not as clear and concise as it could be. Developers should strive to write code that is easy to understand and maintain, which includes avoiding unnecessary assignments.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of this issue and how it can be fixed:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable code\nlet c = 1;\nc = 2;\n\n// Fixed code\nlet c = 2;\n```\n\nIn the vulnerable code, `c` is assigned the value `1`, but this value is never used because `c` is immediately assigned the value `2`. In the fixed code, `c` is only assigned once.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-563: Assignment to Variable without Use ('Unused Variable')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-563",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
