            {
              "id": "43306931-0de3-3e34-be4a-aca7e0bf68cb",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn this case, the vulnerability is related to the use of jQuery's `html()` function. This function can potentially introduce XSS vulnerabilities because it interprets the argument as HTML. If this argument is in any way derived from user input, it can lead to a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function with user-supplied input. Instead, use the `text()` function, which treats the input as plain text, not as HTML code. If you need to include HTML tags in the output, make sure to properly escape them to prevent any code execution.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.html(text_single);\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.text(text_single);\n```\n\nIf you need to include HTML tags in the output, use a function that properly escapes them. For example, if you are using the Underscore.js library, you can use the `_.escape()` function:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.html(_.escape(text_single));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4343fa19-d888-323e-9723-4901abe50158",
              "name": "\"Vulnerability in Dynamic Execution with Eval and Function\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Vulnerability in Dynamic Execution with Eval and Function\" refers to a security vulnerability in JavaScript where an attacker can inject malicious code into the application through the use of `eval()` or `Function()` methods. These methods are used to execute JavaScript code represented as a string, which can be manipulated by an attacker to execute arbitrary code. This can lead to various security issues such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), Remote Code Execution (RCE), and others.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid using `eval()` or `Function()` methods whenever possible. If dynamic script execution is necessary, ensure that the input is properly sanitized and validated to prevent code injection. Use safer alternatives like `JSON.parse()` or `JSON.stringify()` for handling data. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `Function.prototype.bind`, use arrow functions or other methods to bind context. Here is an example:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable code\nFunction.prototype.bind = function bind(that) {\n  // ...\n}\n\n// Recommended fix\nconst bind = (that) => {\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-94",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-94"
                ]
              }
