            {
              "id": "52ddd794-8f02-36a5-a7bc-af6dcdff6ed4",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, it's important to:\n\n1. **Escape User Input**: Always escape user input to make sure that any characters that have a special meaning in HTML are escaped to their HTML entities.\n\n2. **Validate User Input**: Validate user input on the server-side and client-side. Make sure that the input matches the expected format.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly Cookies**: Use HTTPOnly cookies to prevent the session cookies from being accessed through client-side scripts.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the given code, the body is directly manipulated using jQuery which can lead to XSS if the data is user-controlled. Here is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```javascript\nlet userControlledData = \"<div>Safe HTML content</div>\";\nuserControlledData = $('<div/>').text(userControlledData).html(); // Escape user-controlled data\n$(document.body).html(userControlledData); // Safe to use\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires jQuery library to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "58e530b2-67f0-3a02-9faf-256ed44270f9",
              "name": "\"Code Injection Vulnerability Detected\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code is vulnerable to code injection. Code injection is a security vulnerability that allows an attacker to control the code that is executed by your program. In JavaScript, this often involves functions like `eval()`, `setTimeout()`, `setInterval()`, and `Function()`, which can execute arbitrary strings of code. In this case, the `eval()` function is used, which is a common source of code injection vulnerabilities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `eval()` function and similar functions that can execute arbitrary strings of code. Instead, use safer alternatives that do not execute code. For example, if you need to parse JSON data, use `JSON.parse()` instead of `eval()`.\n\nIf you absolutely must use one of these functions, make sure to properly sanitize and validate all inputs to the function. This can help prevent an attacker from injecting malicious code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code is obfuscated, making it difficult to provide a specific fix. However, in general, you should replace the `eval()` function with a safer alternative. For example, if the `eval()` function is being used to parse JSON data, you could replace it with `JSON.parse()`. If the `eval()` function is being used to execute a string of code, consider whether this is necessary and if there is a safer way to achieve the same result.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Code_Injection)\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
