            {
              "id": "5a5ee649-6f79-3a64-afbd-4ac1c6e5c6e0",
              "name": "\"Vulnerability in Dynamic Execution with Eval and Function\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability in dynamic execution with `eval` and `Function` in JavaScript is a serious security issue. It arises when an application uses the `eval` function or the `Function` constructor to execute code that has been formed from strings. This can lead to arbitrary code execution if an attacker can influence the input to these functions.\n\nThe provided code uses the `eval` function to dynamically execute JavaScript code. This is a dangerous practice as it opens up the application to code injection attacks. An attacker could potentially inject malicious code that gets executed by the `eval` function.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid using `eval` and the `Function` constructor to execute dynamically constructed code. If you must use them, ensure that the input is properly sanitized and validated to prevent code injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific fix would depend on the exact requirements of the code. However, in general, you should replace the use of `eval` with safer alternatives. For example, if you're using `eval` to parse JSON, you should use `JSON.parse` instead.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code seems to be obfuscated and it's hard to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to be using the `SyntaxHighlighter` library.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)\n\nPlease note that these links are subject to change and may not be accessible at all times."
