            {
              "id": "5b9ba6f9-56e5-3861-9102-16b493593c24",
              "name": "\"Construct Overriding Obfuscation Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Construct Overriding Obfuscation Vulnerability\" in JavaScript is a type of vulnerability where an attacker can override a constructor to change the behavior of a program. In the provided code, the `Array.prototype.indexOf` function is overridden. This can lead to unexpected behavior if the function is used elsewhere in the code, potentially leading to security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid overriding built-in JavaScript functions. If you need to extend the functionality of a built-in function, create a new function instead of overriding the existing one. This will prevent unexpected behavior and potential security issues.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of overriding the `Array.prototype.indexOf` function, you can create a new function. Here's an example:\n\n```javascript\nfunction indexOf(array, searchElement, fromIndex) {\n    var k;\n    if (array == null) {\n        throw new TypeError('\"array\" is null or not defined');\n    }\n    var O = Object(array);\n    var len = O.length >>> 0;\n    if (len === 0) {\n        return -1;\n    }\n    var n = +fromIndex || 0;\n    if (Math.abs(n) === Infinity) {\n        n = 0;\n    }\n    if (n >= len) {\n        return -1;\n    }\n    k = Math.max(n >= 0 ? n : len - Math.abs(n), 0);\n    while (k < len) {\n        if (k in O && O[k] === searchElement) {\n            return k;\n        }\n        k++;\n    }\n    return -1;\n};\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-749: Exposed Dangerous Method or Function](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/749.html)"
              },
