              "name": "\"Vulnerability in Dynamic Execution with Eval and Function\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability in dynamic execution with `eval` and `Function` in JavaScript is a serious security issue. It arises when an application uses the `eval` function or the `Function` constructor to execute code that has been formed from strings. This can lead to arbitrary code execution if an attacker can influence the input to these functions.\n\nThe provided code uses the `eval` function to execute a string of code. This is a dangerous practice as it opens up the possibility for code injection attacks. If an attacker can control part or all of the string that is passed to `eval`, they can execute arbitrary code in the context of your application.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nAvoid using `eval` and the `Function` constructor as much as possible. If you must use them, make sure that the input is not controlled by the user and is properly sanitized. \n\nConsider using safer alternatives to `eval` and `Function`, such as `JSON.parse` or `JSON.stringify`.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nThe provided code is obfuscated and it's hard to provide a specific fix without knowing the original intent of the code. However, in general, you should avoid using `eval` and instead use safer alternatives.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not seem to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP JavaScript Security](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Code_Injection)\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
