            {
              "id": "6874db91-9fdf-334e-aeae-db665995b67f",
              "name": "\"Code Injection Vulnerability Detected\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code is vulnerable to Code Injection. Code Injection is a type of vulnerability where an attacker can inject malicious code into the existing code, which is then executed by the application. This can lead to various security issues such as data theft, data corruption, denial of service, etc. In this case, the vulnerability lies in the use of the `eval()` function, which executes the code it's given with the privileges of the caller.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using `eval()` and its aliases (`setTimeout()`, `setInterval()`, and `Function()`). These functions can execute dynamically generated code, which is a common source of code injection vulnerabilities. If you must use these functions, make sure the code being executed is not derived from user input or other untrusted sources.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific fix would depend on the exact requirements of your code. However, a general recommendation would be to replace the use of `eval()` with safer alternatives. For example, if you're using `eval()` to parse JSON, you could use `JSON.parse()` instead.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Code Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Code_Injection)\n- [CWE-94: Code Injection](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)\n\nPlease note that these links are subject to change and may not be accessible in the future. Always refer to the latest and most reliable security resources."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-94",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-94"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6a4f213c-c990-3656-b3fd-1eec5d521bf0",
              "name": "\"File Replacement and Local Privilege Escalation Vulnerability due to os.Executable() Behaviour Variation Across Operating Systems\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `os.Executable()` function in Go programming language is used to find the path name for the executable that started the current process. However, there is a variation in its behavior across different operating systems. This variation can lead to a file replacement and local privilege escalation vulnerability.\n\nIn Unix-like operating systems, `os.Executable()` returns a path that is a symbolic link. In contrast, on Windows, it returns the final target of the symbolic link. This discrepancy can be exploited by an attacker to replace the executable file with a malicious one, leading to privilege escalation if the original executable had higher privileges.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, developers should avoid relying on `os.Executable()` to find the path of the current executable. Instead, they should use other means to locate the executable, such as hardcoding the path or using a configuration file. \n\nDevelopers should also ensure that their programs run with the least privileges necessary, to limit the potential damage if an attacker manages to replace the executable.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `os.Executable()`, you can use a constant or a configuration value to determine the path of the executable. For example:\n\n```go\nconst ExecutablePath = \"/path/to/executable\"\n\n// or\n\nconfig := LoadConfig() // LoadConfig is a hypothetical function that loads a configuration\nExecutablePath := config.ExecutablePath\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the built-in `os` package in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-269: Improper Privilege Management](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/269.html)\n- [CWE-59: Improper Link Resolution Before File Access ('Link Following')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/59.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-269",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/269.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-59",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/59.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-269",
                  "CWE-59"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6dacf03d-94de-3f53-81f3-871346fb8263",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability with JQuery's HTML Function; Use Text Function or HTML-Escaping Function Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and is used to generate dynamic HTML content. The JQuery's `html()` function can potentially introduce XSS vulnerabilities if it's used to insert untrusted data. In this case, the `min_pretty` and `this.options.min` variables are directly passed into the `html()` function which can lead to XSS if these variables contain malicious scripts.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function to insert untrusted data. Instead, use JQuery's `text()` function or an HTML-escaping function to ensure that any HTML tags in the data are treated as literal text rather than being interpreted as code. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable line of code with the following:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.min.text(this.decorate(min_pretty, this.options.min));\n```\n\nThis will ensure that any HTML tags in `min_pretty` and `this.options.min` are treated as literal text.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- JQuery\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6f3a4c4b-cd33-3201-a7c0-cc43d669d8b6",
              "name": "Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rate; Recommendation for Storage in CDN or Cloud Buckets",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code is an obfuscated code that uses the `eval()` function. The `eval()` function in JavaScript is a powerful feature that allows the execution of arbitrary JavaScript code represented as a string. However, it is also a common source of security vulnerabilities, as it can potentially execute malicious code. This is especially problematic when the input to `eval()` comes from an untrusted source, such as user input or a file that could not be properly read and validated.\n\nThe vulnerability is related to the exclusion of unreadable files from scans due to a high false positive rate. This could potentially allow an attacker to hide malicious code in such files, bypassing security scans and leading to the execution of the malicious code when the file is processed by the JavaScript code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the following steps are recommended:\n\n1. Avoid using the `eval()` function whenever possible. There are usually safer alternatives for executing JavaScript code dynamically, such as `setTimeout()` and `setInterval()` with function arguments, or using the `Function` constructor.\n\n2. Validate and sanitize all inputs to the `eval()` function. This includes not only user input, but also data read from files or received from network requests.\n\n3. Implement proper error handling for file reading operations. If a file cannot be read properly, it should not be processed further.\n\n4. Store files in a secure manner, such as in a Content Delivery Network (CDN) or cloud storage buckets with proper access controls.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific fix would depend on the exact requirements of your code. However, a general recommendation would be to replace the `eval()` function with a safer alternative, and add proper error handling for file reading operations.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP JavaScript Security](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Code_Injection)\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-94",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-94"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7176c0a3-5021-37af-9a59-89e1c4fdea2f",
              "name": "\"Potential XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and is used to generate dynamic HTML content. The `innerHTML` property in JavaScript can be a potential source of such vulnerabilities. If the data used to set `innerHTML` is not properly sanitized, it can lead to XSS attacks. In the provided code snippet, the `innerHTML` property is set using dynamic input (`t.hours`), which can potentially lead to an XSS vulnerability if `t.hours` contains malicious script.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using `innerHTML` with unsanitized user input. Instead, use `textContent` or `innerText` properties which do not interpret the passed content as HTML, but as plain text. Alternatively, if you need to use `innerHTML`, make sure to sanitize the input data to remove any potential scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable line with:\n\n```javascript\nhoursSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.hours).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "71d99945-26df-39df-b384-9b2a6de83606",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A web application is vulnerable to XSS if it uses unsanitized user input. XSS attacks occur when an attacker uses a web application to send malicious code, generally in the form of a browser side script, to a different end user.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `innerHTML` property is used to insert user-controlled input into the HTML content of an element. This is dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML and JavaScript code, which will be executed in the context of the victim's session.\n\n```javascript\nhoursItem.innerHTML = ('0' + time.hours).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should always treat user input as untrusted data. You should use context-specific output encoding/escaping techniques on all user-supplied input before including it in the output page. \n\nIn this specific case, you should avoid using `innerHTML` to insert user-controlled input. Instead, use safer alternatives like `textContent` or `innerText`, which do not interpret the passed string as HTML, but instead insert it as raw text.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a safer version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```javascript\nhoursItem.textContent = ('0' + time.hours).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "760a12bd-9f13-3986-9be5-cd4be50f0709",
              "name": "Redundant Variable Assignment Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, \"`d` is assigned twice; the first assignment is useless\" is a code smell that indicates a potential issue with variable assignment. This happens when a variable is assigned a value, and then reassigned a new value before the first value is used. The first assignment is therefore unnecessary and can lead to confusion and potential bugs.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, developers should ensure that they only assign values to variables when necessary. If a variable is assigned a value that is never used before it is reassigned, this is a sign that the code could be cleaned up and potentially simplified. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of this issue and how it can be fixed:\n\n```javascript\n// Problematic code\nlet d = 5;\nd = 10;\nconsole.log(d); // Outputs: 10\n\n// Fixed code\nlet d;\nd = 10;\nconsole.log(d); // Outputs: 10\n```\n\nIn the problematic code, `d` is assigned the value `5`, but this value is never used because `d` is immediately reassigned the value `10`. In the fixed code, `d` is only assigned once, eliminating the unnecessary assignment.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n- [CWE-563: Assignment to Variable without Use ('Unused Variable')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-563",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/563.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-563"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7856549e-e4f3-3670-92f8-6ff9deb2bfe0",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A web application is vulnerable to XSS if it uses unsanitized user input. XSS attacks occur when an attacker uses a web application to send malicious code, generally in the form of a browser side script, to a different end user.\n\nIn JavaScript, using `innerHTML` to dynamically insert string values into web page elements can lead to XSS vulnerabilities if the string values are not properly sanitized. This is because `innerHTML` interprets the string as HTML, including any scripts that the string might contain.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities due to dynamic input in `innerHTML`, you should always sanitize user input. This means that you should encode or escape special characters that have special meanings in HTML. \n\nIn addition, you should consider using `textContent` instead of `innerHTML` when inserting text from a source outside of your application. This is because `textContent` does not parse the inserted text as HTML, but instead inserts it as raw text.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```javascript\nnodes[handle].innerHTML = values[handle];\n```\n\nYou should use:\n\n```javascript\nnodes[handle].textContent = values[handle];\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7e840c91-e6fb-369f-a976-c3d15c69f5b2",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A type of XSS vulnerability is when user-controlled data in a HTML string may result in XSS. This happens when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing HTML page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, it is important to:\n\n1. **Escape user input**: This means that you should make sure that any user input is properly escaped, so that it is treated as data rather than code.\n\n2. **Validate user input**: You should not trust user input and should validate it on the server side as well as on the client side.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly cookies**: This attribute can help to mitigate the impact of a potential XSS attack by preventing an attacker from accessing the session cookie via JavaScript.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to escape user input in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\nvar userInput = \"<script>malicious code here</script>\";\nvar safeInput = escape(userInput);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `escape` function is used to make sure that the user input is treated as data rather than code.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7f51ca10-8f51-342f-862e-ca68e881e6d5",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the fact that the `container` variable is directly used to select an element without any sanitization or encoding. If the `container` variable is user-controlled and not properly sanitized, it can lead to an XSS attack.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, it is recommended to:\n\n- Always validate user input: User input should always be validated before it is processed. This includes not only checking for script tags, but also HTML entities and other forms of obfuscation.\n- Use appropriate response headers: By setting the Content-Type and X-Content-Type-Options headers, you can prevent the browser from interpreting files as something else than declared by the content type.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP): CSP is an effective countermeasure to XSS attacks. It allows you to create a whitelist of sources of trusted content, and instructs the browser to only execute or render resources from those sources.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe code should be fixed to ensure that the `container` variable is properly sanitized before use. This can be done using the `text()` function in jQuery, which sets or returns the text content of selected elements. When setting the text content, any less than (<) and greater than (>) characters will be replaced with their HTML entity equivalents, effectively preventing any HTML injection.\n\n```javascript\nthis.$container = $('<div>').text(container);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "84a46721-eb24-3abb-8bdf-bf82d50f6182",
              "name": "\"addEventListener API Vulnerability to Cross Origin Attacks and XSS\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `addEventListener` API in JavaScript is used to register an event to a specific element. This API can be vulnerable to Cross-Origin attacks and Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) if not properly implemented. An attacker can inject malicious scripts into the event handler, which can then be executed when the event is triggered.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `scroll` event is being listened to on the `window` object. If the `scroller` function is not properly sanitized or if it's accepting input from an untrusted source, it can lead to a potential XSS attack.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should:\n\n1. Always validate and sanitize input: Never trust user input. Always validate and sanitize it to ensure it does not contain any malicious code.\n\n2. Use Content Security Policy (CSP): CSP is a security layer that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including XSS and data injection attacks.\n\n3. Use HTTPOnly and Secure flags: These flags can be used to protect cookies from being accessed by client-side scripts, reducing the risk of XSS attacks.\n\n4. Avoid inline scripts: Inline scripts are more susceptible to XSS attacks. Use external scripts instead.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```javascript\n// Assuming scroller is a function that accepts user input\nfunction scroller(e) {\n    var input = e.target.value;\n    // sanitize the input here\n    input = sanitize(input);\n    // rest of the code\n}\n\nwindow.addEventListener('scroll', scroller, false);\n```\n\nIn this code, we assume that `sanitize` is a function that properly sanitizes the user input to prevent XSS attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-345",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-345"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "860231ac-f98b-3755-adbc-3b8813245ce6",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability Risk from User-Controlled Data in `secondsSpan.innerHTML` Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet `secondsSpan.innerHTML = ('0' + t.seconds).slice(-2);` is vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. This is because it directly assigns user-controlled data to `innerHTML`. If an attacker can control the value of `t.seconds`, they can inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, which will be executed when the page is loaded.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this risk, you should always escape user-controlled data before inserting it into the HTML document. This can be done using various methods, such as using `textContent` instead of `innerHTML`, or using the `innerText` property.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```javascript\nsecondsSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.seconds).slice(-2);\n```\n\nIn this version, `textContent` is used instead of `innerHTML`, which automatically escapes any HTML tags in the input, preventing XSS attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
