            {
              "id": "88716043-8dca-3de3-aab8-5497e5329f28",
              "name": "\"Logging Errors for Debugging and Security Monitoring in Empty Catch Block\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, an empty catch block suppresses errors silently. This means that when an error occurs within a try block, the catch block that follows it is supposed to handle the error. However, if the catch block is empty, the error is suppressed and not handled, which can lead to unexpected behavior in the program. This is a vulnerability because it can make debugging difficult and can also pose a security risk if the error is related to a security issue.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always handle errors in the catch block. This can be done by logging the error, which can help with debugging and security monitoring. It is also recommended to avoid suppressing errors silently, as this can make it difficult to identify and fix issues in the code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix this vulnerability in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\ntry {\n  // code that may throw an error\n} catch (error) {\n  console.error(error); // log the error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the catch block is not empty and it logs the error when it occurs. This allows for easier debugging and security monitoring.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Error Handling](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Error_Handling_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-390: Detection of Error Condition Without Action](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-390",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-390"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "891c5c58-8ad8-3d43-8f0d-15313d4986fa",
              "name": "Potential ReDoS Vulnerability Due to Use of `c` Function Argument in RegExp() Call: Consider Hardcoded Regexes, Input Validation, or Regex Checking/Sanitization Libraries for Mitigation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided JavaScript code is vulnerable to a potential Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) attack due to the use of the `c` function argument in the `RegExp()` call. ReDoS is a type of Denial of Service attack that exploits the fact that most Regular Expression implementations may reach extreme situations that cause them to work very slowly (exponentially related to input size). An attacker can then cause a program using a Regular Expression to enter these extreme situations and then hang for a very long time.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, consider the following:\n\n1. **Hardcoded Regexes**: Instead of dynamically creating regular expressions, use hardcoded regular expressions whenever possible. This reduces the risk of creating inefficient or dangerous regular expressions from user input or other untrusted sources.\n\n2. **Input Validation**: Always validate user input before using it in a regular expression. This can prevent many types of attacks, including ReDoS.\n\n3. **Regex Checking/Sanitization Libraries**: Use libraries that can check or sanitize regular expressions to ensure they are not susceptible to ReDoS attacks. These libraries can analyze a regular expression and determine if it is potentially dangerous.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is the `RegExp()` call with the `c` function argument. To fix this, you could replace the dynamic regular expression with a hardcoded one, or validate the `c` argument before using it in the `RegExp()` call.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1333",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1333.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1333"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8978b693-4863-3fc2-8d21-785ea1ab9359",
              "name": "Secure Regex Against User Input to Prevent ReDoS Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nRegular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) is a type of Denial of Service attack. It occurs when a regular expression (regex) is used to process user-supplied input and the regex is vulnerable to catastrophic backtracking. Catastrophic backtracking happens when a regex takes a very long time to evaluate certain inputs, potentially causing the application to become unresponsive or to crash.\n\nIn JavaScript, this vulnerability can be exploited if an attacker can control a part of the regular expression string. The attacker can provide a specially crafted input that causes the regex to take a long time to evaluate, effectively causing a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, follow these general guidelines:\n\n1. Avoid using regular expressions if possible. If you must use them, make sure they are simple and not prone to catastrophic backtracking.\n2. Limit the size of the input that a regular expression can process.\n3. Use a timeout when evaluating a regular expression. If the regex takes too long to evaluate, abort the operation.\n4. Use tools to check your regular expressions for potential ReDoS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of a vulnerable regex and how to fix it:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable regex\nvar regex = /^([a-z])+$/;\n\n// Fixed regex\nvar regex = /^([a-z]{1,10})+$/;\n```\n\nIn the fixed regex, we limit the number of characters that can be matched to 10. This prevents an attacker from causing a ReDoS by supplying a very long string.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-185",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/185.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-185"
                ]
              }
