            {
              "id": "9347ffaa-6e93-3aa3-a0bb-d99789f49d5b",
              "name": "\"Non-standard and Improperly Named Objects Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript programming, obfuscated object names that don't follow naming standards and best practices can lead to confusion, misinterpretation, and potential security vulnerabilities. This is because obfuscated names can hide the true intent of the code, making it difficult for developers to understand what the code is doing, and potentially allowing malicious code to be hidden within the application.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to follow naming standards and best practices for JavaScript programming. This includes using clear, descriptive names for variables, functions, and objects, and avoiding the use of obfuscated names. Additionally, code reviews should be conducted to ensure that all code follows these standards and best practices.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix this issue:\n\n```javascript\n// Bad practice\nvar a = \"Hello, World!\";\n\n// Good practice\nvar greetingMessage = \"Hello, World!\";\n```\n\nIn the bad practice example, the variable name `a` is obfuscated and does not clearly indicate what it is used for. In the good practice example, the variable name `greetingMessage` is clear and descriptive, making the code easier to understand and less likely to hide potential security vulnerabilities.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-pdf-archive/OWASP_Code_Review_Guide_v2.pdf)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-111: Direct Use of Unsafe JNI](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/111.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-111",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/111.html"
