                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "98094ac4-88be-302d-8275-f0d32c8d9796",
              "name": "Potential ReDoS vulnerability due to RegExp() being called with a `b` function argument in your application.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `RegExp()` function in JavaScript is used to create a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern. When this function is called with a `b` function argument, it can potentially allow an attacker to cause a Regular Expression Denial-of-Service (ReDoS) within your application. This is because the `RegExp()` function blocks the main thread, causing the application to hang or become unresponsive.\n\nReDoS is a form of Denial of Service (DoS) attack that exploits the fact that most Regular Expression implementations may reach extreme situations that cause them to work very slowly (exponentially related to input size). An attacker can then cause a program using a Regular Expression to enter these extreme situations and then hang for a very long time.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use hardcoded regular expressions instead of passing a function argument to `RegExp()`. If your regular expression is run on user-controlled input, consider performing input validation to ensure that the input is safe before running the regular expression on it. \n\nYou can also use a regular expression checking or sanitization library, such as [recheck](https://www.npmjs.com/package/recheck), to verify that the regular expression does not appear vulnerable to ReDoS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `RegExp()` with a function argument, use a hardcoded regular expression. For example, instead of:\n\n```javascript\nlet pattern = new RegExp(someFunction());\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```javascript\nlet pattern = /hardcoded_pattern/;\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-1333",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1333.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-1333"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9e538bf6-b09e-37e5-a089-084a04b5e13e",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `innerHTML` property is used to insert user-controlled input (`t.minutes`) into the HTML document. This is dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use the principle of least privilege: Only allow necessary permissions for the user.\n- Validate input: Ensure that the input matches the expected format.\n- Escape output: Ensure that any output is properly escaped.\n- Use secure APIs: Use APIs, such as `innerText`, that automatically escape output.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP): This can help to mitigate the impact of any potential XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `innerHTML`, use `textContent` or `innerText` which do not interpret the passed content as HTML, but instead insert it as raw text.\n\n```javascript\nminutesSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.minutes).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
