            {
              "id": "afaebb8f-dba9-3409-8280-116c1b541572",
              "name": "Useless Comparison Operation Detection",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, a comparison operation such as `d == d` or `d != d` is always true. This is because JavaScript uses the IEEE 754 standard for floating point arithmetic. According to this standard, all numbers except NaN (Not a Number) are equal to themselves. Therefore, a comparison operation like `d == d` or `d != d` is always true, unless `d` is NaN.\n\nThis can lead to logical errors in the code, especially if the developer intended to check for NaN but used a comparison operation instead of the appropriate function. This can potentially lead to unexpected behavior and vulnerabilities in the application.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this issue, developers should use the appropriate functions to check for NaN. In JavaScript, the `isNaN()` function can be used to check if a value is NaN. This function returns true if the value is NaN, and false otherwise.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using a comparison operation like `d == d` or `d != d`, use the `isNaN()` function to check for NaN. Here is an example:\n\n```javascript\nlet d = NaN;\n\n// Incorrect\nif (d != d) {\n  console.log('d is NaN');\n}\n\n// Correct\nif (isNaN(d)) {\n  console.log('d is NaN');\n}\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A3: Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE-480): Use of Incorrect Operator](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/480.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-480",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/480.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-480"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b54c5f9b-b6c1-3616-8bf0-c7a46ef0d9e2",
              "name": "\"Exclusion of Unreadable Files from Scans Due to High False Positive Rates\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript programming, a common vulnerability arises when files are minified, compressed, obfuscated, or otherwise made unreadable. While these practices can be a strong indicator of maliciousness, they also have a relatively higher false positive (FP) rate. This means that legitimate, non-malicious files can sometimes be flagged as malicious, leading to unnecessary alerts and potential disruption of normal operations. \n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is highly recommended to store such files in Content Delivery Networks (CDNs), cloud buckets, or similar storage solutions. This not only helps to reduce the risk of false positives but also helps to keep the codebase readable and maintainable. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nWhile there's no direct source code fix for this issue, as it's more about the organization of your code and files, you can follow these general steps:\n\n1. Avoid minifying, compressing, or obfuscating files unless absolutely necessary.\n2. If you must use these practices, store the files in a CDN or cloud bucket.\n3. Keep your codebase as readable as possible. This includes using clear variable names, adding comments to explain complex sections of code, and following other best practices for code readability.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE- obfuscation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1166.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b566b310-7dc6-3d08-acaf-d0aee935bfb6",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability due to Dynamic Input in innerHTML",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `innerHTML` property is used to insert user-controlled input (`t.seconds`) into the HTML document. This is dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject arbitrary HTML or JavaScript code, leading to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use the principle of least privilege: Only allow necessary permissions for the code to execute.\n- Validate input: Ensure that the input matches the expected format.\n- Escape output: Make sure that any user-supplied input is treated as display text and not executable script.\n- Use secure APIs: Some APIs provide automatic escaping to prevent XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `innerHTML`, use `textContent` or `innerText` which do not interpret the passed content as HTML, but instead insert it as raw text.\n\n```javascript\nsecondsSpan.textContent = ('0' + t.seconds).slice(-2);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
