            {
              "id": "b7494e37-dc7d-38e9-90e1-8615b73c4b49",
              "name": "Code Injection Vulnerability Detected in 'exec.Command' Input",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `exec.CommandContext(ctx, \"sh\", \"-c\", cmd).CombinedOutput()` function in Go programming language is vulnerable to code injection attacks. This vulnerability occurs when an attacker can control the `cmd` input to the function. If the `cmd` input is not properly sanitized, an attacker can inject arbitrary shell commands, which will be executed with the same privileges as the program.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using user-controlled input in `exec.Command` or any similar functions that execute system commands. If it's necessary to use user input, make sure to properly sanitize and validate the input before using it. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of passing the entire command as a single string, pass the command and its arguments as separate strings to `exec.CommandContext`. This way, the shell doesn't process any part of the command as shell instructions.\n\nHere is an example of how to fix the code:\n\n```go\n// cmd is a slice of strings, where the first element is the command and the rest are its arguments\ncmd := []string{\"ls\", \"-l\", \"/path/to/directory\"}\n\nreturn exec.CommandContext(ctx, cmd[0], cmd[1:]...).CombinedOutput()\n```\n\nIn this example, even if an attacker controls the elements of `cmd` slice, they can't inject arbitrary shell commands because the elements are treated as arguments to the `ls` command, not as shell instructions.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires only the standard library of Go programming language.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Code_Injection)\n- [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
