                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript programming, a common vulnerability arises when files are minified, compressed, obfuscated, or otherwise made unreadable. While these practices can be a strong indicator of maliciousness, they also have a relatively higher false positive (FP) rate. This means that legitimate, non-malicious files can sometimes be flagged as malicious, leading to unnecessary alerts and potential disruption of normal operations. \n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is highly recommended to store such files in Content Delivery Networks (CDNs), cloud buckets, or similar storage solutions. This not only helps to reduce the risk of false positives but also helps to keep the codebase readable and maintainable. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nWhile there's no direct source code fix for this issue, as it's more about the organization of your code and files, you can follow these general steps:\n\n1. Avoid minifying, compressing, or obfuscating files unless absolutely necessary.\n2. If you must use these practices, store the files in a CDN or cloud bucket.\n3. Keep your codebase as readable as possible. This includes using clear variable names, adding comments to explain complex sections of code, and following other best practices for code readability.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE- obfuscation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/1166.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
