            {
              "id": "d33ae50f-b518-3d88-bd59-30684b3f38f6",
              "name": "Detected Insecure Deserialization Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure Deserialization is a vulnerability that occurs when untrusted data is used to abuse the logic of an application, inflict a denial of service (DoS) attack, or execute arbitrary code upon it being deserialized. It also happens to be one of the OWASP Top 10 Application Security Risks.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the `eval()` function is used, which is a potential security risk as it allows execution of arbitrary JavaScript code. This can lead to Insecure Deserialization if the input is not properly sanitized or validated.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using `eval()` function. If it's absolutely necessary, ensure that the input passed to it is properly sanitized and validated. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the `eval()` function with safer alternatives like `JSON.parse()` or `JSON.stringify()`. These functions do not execute the JavaScript code, hence are safer to use.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not seem to have any explicit library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html)"
              },
