            {
              "id": "e40ed51b-31eb-389b-86eb-a246648d2ad5",
              "name": "\"Potential XSS Vulnerability with JQuery's HTML Function: Use Text Function or HTML Escaping Function\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the jQuery `.html()` function is used, which can potentially introduce an XSS vulnerability if the input is not properly sanitized. The `.html()` function gets the HTML contents of the first element in the set of matched elements or set the HTML contents of every matched element. If you try to insert content using this function, it will treat the input as HTML and any script included can be executed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `.html()` function with user-supplied input. Instead, use functions that treat input as text and not as HTML, such as the `.text()` function. Alternatively, you can use HTML escaping functions to ensure any characters that have special meaning in HTML are properly escaped.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the `.html()` function with the `.text()` function:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.max.text(this.decorate(this.options.p_values[this.options.max]));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the jQuery library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e73722db-deb3-3a6e-a23e-64274540dec7",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the vulnerability lies in the fact that user-controlled HTML data is being processed without proper sanitization or validation. This can lead to an XSS attack if an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into the user-controlled data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, it is recommended to:\n\n- Use frameworks that automatically escape XSS by design, such as Ruby on Rails, React JS, etc.\n- Escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (body, attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) will resolve Reflected and Stored XSS vulnerabilities.\n- Apply context-sensitive encoding when modifying the browser document on the client side acts against DOM XSS.\n- Enable a Content Security Policy (CSP) as a safety net to mitigate the impact of any potential XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code does not have any library dependencies. However, it is recommended to use a library such as DOMPurify to sanitize the user-controlled HTML data. Here is an example of how to use DOMPurify:\n\n```javascript\nvar DOMPurify = require('dompurify');\nvar sanitizedHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(userControlledHTML);\nreturn '\\\\b([a-z_]|)' + sanitizedHTML.replace(/ /g, '(?=:)\\\\b|\\\\b([a-z_\\\\*]|\\\\*|)') + '(?=:)\\\\b';\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e899e65c-4114-3f6e-a74b-eae12def5e84",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the jQuery `html()` function is used to set the HTML content of an element. This function does not escape or sanitize the input, which means that if the input contains script tags or other potentially harmful HTML, it will be executed by the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function with untrusted input. Instead, use the `text()` function, which automatically escapes HTML tags, or use a function that explicitly escapes HTML, such as `HtmlUtils.setHtml()`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable line with:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.min.text(this.decorate(this.options.p_values[this.options.min]));\n```\n\nOr, if you need to include HTML tags in the output:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.min.html(HtmlUtils.setHtml(this.decorate(this.options.p_values[this.options.min])));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following libraries:\n\n- jQuery\n- A library that provides the `HtmlUtils.setHtml()` function, such as Underscore.js or a custom utility library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ec00637b-cbdd-3c04-b24c-d2f1f83b4e91",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn this case, the potential XSS vulnerability arises from the use of jQuery's `html()` function. This function can potentially execute JavaScript code, making it a common target for XSS attacks. If the `text_from` variable in the provided code snippet contains malicious script, it will be executed when the function is called.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function with untrusted data. Instead, use jQuery's `text()` function for plain strings, which does not parse the passed data as HTML. If you need to include HTML tags in the user input, use a function that escapes the HTML entities, such as `HtmlUtils.setHtml()`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable line of code with one of the following, depending on your needs:\n\nFor plain text:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.from.text(text_from);\n```\n\nFor HTML content:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.from.html(HtmlUtils.setHtml(text_from));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following libraries:\n\n- jQuery\n- HtmlUtils (if you choose to use `HtmlUtils.setHtml()`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ec183d18-573a-30d8-bffe-5852e03f13b2",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerabilities from User-Controlled Data in Methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn JavaScript, methods like `innerHTML`, `outerHTML`, or `document.write` can introduce XSS vulnerabilities when they are used to insert user-controlled data into the DOM. These methods interpret the inserted data as HTML, which can include potentially harmful scripts.\n\nIn the provided code example, the `innerHTML` method is used to insert user-controlled data (`t.days`) into the `daysSpan` element. If `t.days` contains a malicious script, it will be executed when the `daysSpan` element is rendered.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use text content property instead of HTML content property. In JavaScript, use `textContent` instead of `innerHTML` or `outerHTML`.\n- Use secure methods for dynamically updating an HTML page. For example, use `element.textContent = string` instead of `element.innerHTML = string`.\n- Validate and sanitize user input. Use a trusted library or framework that automatically escapes user input.\n- Use Content Security Policy (CSP) to reduce the severity of any XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable line of code with:\n\n```javascript\ndaysSpan.textContent = t.days;\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "eca19c6a-076e-3875-8609-048c95d2bc03",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A type of XSS vulnerability is when user-controlled data in a HTML string may result in XSS. This happens when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing HTML page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, it is important to:\n\n1. **Escape user input**: This means that you should make sure that any user input is properly escaped, so that it is treated as data rather than code.\n\n2. **Validate user input**: You should not trust user input and should validate it on the server side as well as on the client side.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly cookies**: This attribute can help to mitigate the impact of a potential XSS attack by preventing an attacker from accessing the session cookie via JavaScript.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to escape user input in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\nvar userInput = \"<script>malicious code here</script>\";\nvar safeInput = escape(userInput);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `escape` function is used to make sure that the user input is treated as data rather than code.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "eeb510f9-9b02-3013-a881-f29fb61e47ca",
              "name": "Secure Regex Against User Input to Prevent ReDoS Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nRegular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS) is a type of Denial of Service attack. It occurs when a regular expression (regex) is used to process user-supplied input and the regex is vulnerable to catastrophic backtracking. Catastrophic backtracking happens when a regex takes a very long time to evaluate certain inputs, potentially causing the application to become unresponsive or to crash.\n\nIn JavaScript, this vulnerability can be exploited if an attacker can control a part of the regular expression string. The attacker can provide a specially crafted input that causes the regex to take a long time to evaluate, effectively causing a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, follow these general guidelines:\n\n1. Avoid using regular expressions if possible. If you must use them, make sure they are simple and not prone to catastrophic backtracking.\n2. Limit the size of the input that a regular expression can process.\n3. Use a timeout when evaluating a regular expression. If the regex takes too long to evaluate, abort the operation.\n4. Use tools to check your regular expressions for potential ReDoS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of a vulnerable regex and how to fix it:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable regex\nvar regex = /^([a-z])+$/;\n\n// Fixed regex\nvar regex = /^([a-z]{1,10})+$/;\n```\n\nIn the fixed regex, we limit the number of characters that can be matched to 10. This prevents an attacker from causing a ReDoS by supplying a very long string.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP ReDoS](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service_-_ReDoS)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-185",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/185.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-185"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ef6889c3-5235-38e3-8b18-8cc5109c043c",
              "name": "\"Logging Errors for Debugging and Security Monitoring in Empty Catch Block\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, an empty catch block suppresses errors silently. This means that when an error occurs within a try block, the catch block that follows it is supposed to handle the error. However, if the catch block is empty, the error is suppressed and not handled, which can lead to unexpected behavior in the program. This is a vulnerability because it can make debugging difficult and can also pose a security risk if the error is related to a security issue.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always handle errors in the catch block. This can be done by logging the error, which can help with debugging and security monitoring. It is also recommended to avoid suppressing errors silently, as this can make it difficult to identify and fix issues in the code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix this vulnerability in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\ntry {\n  // code that may throw an error\n} catch (error) {\n  console.error(error); // log the error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the catch block is not empty and it logs the error when it occurs. This allows for easier debugging and security monitoring.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Error Handling](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Error_Handling_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-390: Detection of Error Condition Without Action](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-390",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/390.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-390"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f0616646-bf71-3a69-bd45-8f23c8259d57",
              "name": "\"Potential XSS Vulnerability with JQuery's html Function: Use text Function for Plain Strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for HTML Escaping\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A web application is vulnerable to XSS if it uses unsanitized user input. jQuery's `html()` function can potentially open up an application to XSS attacks if it's used to insert user-controlled input.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `label.html(submitMsg).show(2000);`, the `html()` function is used to insert `submitMsg` into the `label` element. If `submitMsg` is user-controlled and not properly sanitized, this could lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function with user-controlled input. Instead, use the `text()` function for plain strings, which does not interpret the input as HTML. If you need to insert HTML content, make sure to properly sanitize it before insertion. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the vulnerable code with the following:\n\n```javascript\nlabel.text(submitMsg).show(2000);\n```\n\nIf `submitMsg` contains HTML that needs to be rendered, use a library or function that properly escapes HTML. For example, if you're using underscore.js, you can use `_.escape()`:\n\n```javascript\nlabel.html(_.escape(submitMsg)).show(2000);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires jQuery to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f1ab0b1a-1167-340f-ad1d-cb9655aa66ce",
              "name": "\"Crypto.pseudoRandomBytes()/Math.random() exhibits cryptographic weakness.\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `crypto.pseudoRandomBytes()` function in Node.js and `Math.random()` function in JavaScript are used to generate random numbers. However, these functions are not suitable for generating random numbers in a cryptographic context, as they do not provide cryptographic strength randomness. This means that the numbers generated by these functions can be predictable, which can lead to various security vulnerabilities, such as predictable session identifiers, weak cryptographic keys, and other security risks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should use a cryptographically strong random number generator. In Node.js, you can use the `crypto.randomBytes()` function, which generates cryptographically strong pseudo-random data. In the browser, you can use the `window.crypto.getRandomValues()` function, which generates cryptographically random values.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix this vulnerability in Node.js:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable code\nvar crypto = require('crypto');\nvar randomBytes = crypto.pseudoRandomBytes(16);\n\n// Fixed code\nvar crypto = require('crypto');\nvar randomBytes = crypto.randomBytes(16);\n```\n\nAnd here is an example of how to fix this vulnerability in the browser:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable code\nvar randomValue = Math.random();\n\n// Fixed code\nvar array = new Uint32Array(1);\nwindow.crypto.getRandomValues(array);\nvar randomValue = array[0];\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Node.js Security Cheat Sheet - Cryptographic Storage](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html#cryptographic-storage)\n- [CWE-338: Use of Cryptographically Weak Pseudo-Random Number Generator (PRNG)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f229db4d-4103-31f6-9807-eab13ee70bcd",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided JavaScript code, the vulnerability lies in the fact that user-controlled HTML data is being processed without proper sanitization or validation. This can lead to an XSS attack if an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into the user-controlled data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, it is recommended to:\n\n- Use frameworks that automatically escape XSS by design, such as Ruby on Rails, React JS, etc.\n- Escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (body, attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) will resolve Reflected and Stored XSS vulnerabilities.\n- Apply context-sensitive encoding when modifying the browser document on the client side acts against DOM XSS.\n- Enable a Content Security Policy (CSP) as a safety net to mitigate the impact of any potential XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code does not have any library dependencies. However, it is recommended to use a library such as DOMPurify to sanitize the user-controlled HTML data. Here is an example of how to use DOMPurify:\n\n```javascript\nvar DOMPurify = require('dompurify');\nvar sanitizedHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(userControlledHTML);\nreturn '\\\\b([a-z_]|)' + sanitizedHTML.replace(/ /g, '(?=:)\\\\b|\\\\b([a-z_\\\\*]|\\\\*|)') + '(?=:)\\\\b';\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
