            {
              "id": "f54c2cde-0fc1-39ea-a925-84967761d5e9",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn this case, the vulnerability is related to the use of jQuery's `html()` function. This function can potentially introduce XSS vulnerabilities because it interprets the argument as HTML. If this argument is in any way derived from user input, it can lead to a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using the `html()` function with user-supplied input. Instead, use the `text()` function, which treats the input as plain text, not as HTML code. If you need to include HTML tags in the output, make sure to properly escape them to prevent any code execution.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.html(text_single);\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.text(text_single);\n```\n\nIf you need to include HTML tags in the output, use a function that properly escapes them. For example, if you are using the Underscore.js library, you can use the `_.escape()` function:\n\n```javascript\nthis.$cache.single.html(_.escape(text_single));\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the jQuery library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f591bc2b-14ce-3ace-a150-f66c40dee913",
              "name": "\"XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data Anti-Pattern is a common security vulnerability in JavaScript programming. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the given code snippet, the `ajaxChimp` function is vulnerable to XSS attacks if the `options` parameter is controlled by the user and not properly sanitized.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use frameworks that automatically escape XSS by design, such as Ruby on Rails, React JS, etc.\n- Escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (body, attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) will resolve Reflected and Stored XSS vulnerabilities.\n- Apply context-sensitive encoding when modifying the browser document on the client side acts against DOM XSS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe `options` parameter should be properly sanitized before being passed to the `ajaxChimp` function. Here's an example of how you can sanitize the `options` object using the `DOMPurify.sanitize` method:\n\n```javascript\nvar cleanOptions = DOMPurify.sanitize(options);\n$(selector).ajaxChimp(cleanOptions);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following libraries to execute properly:\n\n- jQuery\n- ajaxChimp\n- DOMPurify (for the fix)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f606dd93-9272-3266-83de-458c274590e9",
              "name": "\"addEventListener API Vulnerability to Cross Origin Attacks and XSS\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, the `addEventListener` API is used to register an event handler to a specific event such as click, mouseover, etc. on an element. However, this API does not validate the origin of the event. This means that it can be exploited to perform Cross Origin attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS). XSS is a type of injection attack where malicious scripts are injected into trusted websites. The attacker can use these scripts to steal sensitive information, manipulate web content, or carry out other harmful actions.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always validate the origin of events. This can be done by checking the `origin` property of the event object in the event handler. If the origin is not expected, the event handler should not process the event.\n\nAdditionally, it is also recommended to use Content Security Policy (CSP) to prevent XSS attacks. CSP is a security layer that helps detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including XSS and data injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to validate the origin in an event handler:\n\n```javascript\nelement.addEventListener('message', function(event) {\n  // Check the origin of the event\n  if (event.origin !== 'http://expected.origin.com') {\n    // If the origin is not expected, do not process the event\n    return;\n  }\n\n  // Process the event\n  // ...\n});\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-346: Origin Validation Error](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-345",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/345.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-345"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f736c9a3-34bd-385f-9de1-86f8bf223faa",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of security vulnerability that enables attackers to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. A type of XSS vulnerability is when user-controlled data in a HTML string may result in XSS. This happens when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing HTML page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo prevent XSS vulnerabilities, it is important to:\n\n1. **Escape user input**: This means that you should make sure that any user input is properly escaped, so that it is treated as data rather than code.\n\n2. **Validate user input**: You should not trust user input and should validate it on the server side as well as on the client side.\n\n3. **Use HTTPOnly cookies**: This attribute can help to mitigate the impact of a potential XSS attack by preventing an attacker from accessing the session cookie via JavaScript.\n\n4. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**: Implementing CSP can effectively reduce XSS risks by declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple example of how to escape user input in JavaScript:\n\n```javascript\nvar userInput = \"<script>malicious code here</script>\";\nvar safeInput = escape(userInput);\n```\n\nIn this example, the `escape` function is used to make sure that the user input is treated as data rather than code.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "fabd0cd4-da68-3e59-865f-ee07bb708b20",
              "name": "Potential XSS vulnerability with JQuery's html function; use text function for plain strings or HtmlUtils.setHtml for html escaping.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a type of injection security vulnerability where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. In JavaScript, particularly when using jQuery's `html()` function, this vulnerability can be exploited if user input is not properly sanitized before being rendered on the webpage.\n\nThe `html()` function in jQuery sets or returns the content (innerHTML) of selected elements. However, if this function is used to include user input without proper sanitization, it can lead to XSS attacks. This is because the `html()` function does not escape any HTML and JavaScript content, which means that any script included in the input will be executed when the content is rendered.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `text()` function instead of `html()` when the string is plain text. The `text()` function escapes the HTML and ensures that any included script is not executed.\n\nIf the string contains HTML that needs to be rendered, use a function that escapes HTML such as edx's `HtmlUtils.setHtml()`. This function ensures that any script included in the input is not executed when the content is rendered.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```javascript\n$(\"#element\").html(userInput);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```javascript\n$(\"#element\").text(userInput);\n```\n\nOr, if HTML needs to be rendered:\n\n```javascript\nHtmlUtils.setHtml($(\"#element\"), userInput);\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "fc007494-da8e-316b-b1f4-82307709132d",
              "name": "\"Vulnerability in Dynamic Execution with Eval and Function\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Vulnerability in Dynamic Execution with Eval and Function\" refers to a security vulnerability in JavaScript where an attacker can inject malicious code into the application through the use of `eval()` or `Function()` methods. These methods are used to execute JavaScript code represented as a string, which can be manipulated by an attacker to execute arbitrary code.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid using `eval()` and `Function()` methods whenever possible. If you must use them, make sure the input is properly sanitized and validated to prevent code injection attacks. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is not clear as the code snippet is incomplete. However, if the `Function.prototype.bind` method is being used with user-supplied input, it could potentially lead to a code injection vulnerability. \n\nHere's a general example of how to mitigate such a vulnerability:\n\n```javascript\n// Vulnerable code\nvar userSuppliedCode = \"...\"; // This could be any code supplied by the user\nvar func = new Function(userSuppliedCode);\nfunc();\n\n// Mitigated code\nvar userSuppliedCode = \"...\"; // This could be any code supplied by the user\n// Validate and sanitize the user-supplied code before using it\nvar sanitizedCode = sanitize(userSuppliedCode); // Implement this function based on your needs\nvar func = new Function(sanitizedCode);\nfunc();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not have any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-94",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-94"
                ]
              }
            }
